sing to fly on United metal over the Pacific instead of Star Alliance membe=
r EVA Air). I suspect I won=E2=80=99t be alone.

That, of course, is a good reason for United to give in to Starlink=E2=80=
=99s insistence that service be free; yes, that means giving up on an ancil=
lary revenue stream, but in theory they should make up for that with more t=
icket sales, at least for a while. In the long run, to the extent that Star=
link actually changes flyer preferences is the extent to which other airlin=
es will have to follow suit and intall Starlink themselves. Air France alre=
ady has announced exactly that ( https://corporate.airfrance.com/en/news/ai=
r-france-launches-free-ultra-high-speed-wi-fi-board-all-its-aircraft ).

Starlink can handle unlimited free access thanks to its constellation of lo=
w Earth orbit satellites; other satellite providers use fewer, further sate=
llites to provide coverage, which means lower speeds, higher latency, and m=
ore importantly, more limited bandwidth (Joanna Stern has a good overview o=
f the different offerings in the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/=
tech/personal-tech/inflight-wifi-tested-airlines-flying-9cd94d56 ) ). This =
last bit is what makes Starlink=E2=80=99s insistence on free so clever: whi=
le other satellite providers could always compete on price, they face hard =
constraints on bandwidth, which means that creating a market expectation th=
at airline wifi is free makes it much harder to compete. Indeed, at this po=
int it seems reasonable to assume that Starlink will eventually dominate th=
e market completely: other airlines will need to match United and Air Franc=
e, they will have to do so on Starlink=E2=80=99s terms, and that will creat=
e consumer expectations that other satellite providers will have a hard tim=
e matching.

Starlink exists, of course, because of SpaceX, and the dramatically lower l=
aunch costs Musk and company achieved in defiance of expert assumptions. It=
 seems like the obvious winner now, but it wasn=E2=80=99t at all obvious a =
decade ago; it remains to be seen if we will look at the self-driving tech =
stack similarly in 2034.

